<h2>The Fertility Question: Enclomiphene's Biggest Advantage</h2>

<div class="vs-grid">
  <div class="vs-card winner">
    <h3>‚úÖ Enclomiphene: Preserves Fertility</h3>
    <ul style="margin: 16px 0;">
      <li><strong>Stimulates LH and FSH</strong> (the hormones that make sperm)</li>
      <li><strong>Sperm count maintained or improved</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Can conceive naturally</strong> while on treatment</li>
      <li><strong>No fertility recovery needed</strong> when stopping</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="background: #ecfdf5; padding: 12px; border-radius: 8px; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 0.9rem;"><strong>Real-world:</strong> Men on enclomiphene report normal or improved sperm counts. Many successfully father children while on treatment.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="vs-card">
    <h3>‚ùå Traditional TRT: Suppresses Fertility</h3>
    <ul style="margin: 16px 0;">
      <li><strong>Shuts down LH and FSH</strong> (near-zero levels)</li>
      <li><strong>70-90% reduction in sperm count</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Many men become infertile</strong> (azoospermic)</li>
      <li><strong>Recovery takes 3-24 months</strong> after stopping (may be permanent)</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="background: #fef2f2; padding: 12px; border-radius: 8px; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 0.9rem;"><strong>Real-world:</strong> 10-15% of men never recover fertility after long-term TRT. If you want kids in the next 5-10 years, traditional TRT is risky.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h2>Testosterone Results: How They Compare</h2>

<h3>Enclomiphene Results:</h3>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #f5f3ff 0%, #ede9fe 100%); border: 2px solid #8b5cf6; border-radius: var(--r); padding: 24px; margin: 24px 0;">
  <p style="font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 8px;">Typical Enclomiphene Response:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Before:</strong> 300 ng/dL total testosterone</li>
    <li><strong>After 8 weeks:</strong> 600-750 ng/dL (2-2.5x increase)</li>
    <li><strong>LH/FSH:</strong> Increases 2-3x (maintains fertility)</li>
    <li><strong>Symptom improvement:</strong> 70-80% of men report significant benefit</li>
  </ul>
  <p style="margin-top: 16px; font-size: 0.9rem;"><strong>Limitation:</strong> Can't push testosterone above ~800 ng/dL. If you need very high levels (>1,000), traditional TRT is better.</p>
</div>

<h3>Traditional TRT Results:</h3>

<div style="background: #fef3c7; border: 2px solid #f59e0b; border-radius: var(--r); padding: 24px; margin: 24px 0;">
  <p style="font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 8px;">Typical TRT Response:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Before:</strong> 300 ng/dL total testosterone</li>
    <li><strong>After 8 weeks:</strong> 600-1,200 ng/dL (dose-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>LH/FSH:</strong> Near zero (testicular shutdown)</li>
    <li><strong>Symptom improvement:</strong> 85-95% of men report significant benefit</li>
  </ul>
  <p style="margin-top: 16px; font-size: 0.9rem;"><strong>Advantage:</strong> Can achieve any testosterone level desired. More predictable dosing.</p>
</div>

<h2>Convenience: Oral Pill vs Injections</h2>

<div class="vs-grid">
  <div class="vs-card winner">
    <h3>üíä Enclomiphene: Oral Pill</h3>
    <p style="margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Dosing:</strong> 12.5-25mg once daily OR twice weekly</p>
    <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
    <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
      <li>No needles, no injection pain</li>
      <li>Easy to travel with</li>
      <li>Discreet (just take a pill)</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="margin-top: 12px;"><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
    <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
      <li>Must remember daily (or twice weekly)</li>
      <li>Some men prefer "set it and forget it" injections</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="vs-card">
    <h3>üíâ Traditional TRT: Injections</h3>
    <p style="margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Dosing:</strong> 100-200mg testosterone weekly (or biweekly)</p>
    <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
    <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
      <li>Once-weekly dosing (less frequent)</li>
      <li>Very stable levels with proper protocol</li>
      <li>Gel/patch options available (no injections)</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="margin-top: 12px;"><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
    <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
      <li>Needle phobia barrier</li>
      <li>Injection site pain/bruising</li>
      <li>Gels can transfer to partners/kids</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

